Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase and the App Router patterns. Let me plan the migration:

**Files to create in `app/`:**

1. **`app/layout.tsx`** — Root layout (replaces `_app.js` + `_document.js`)
   - Server component (default)
   - HTML/body tags
   - Import globals.css
   - Wrap with AppProvider (which needs to become a client component)
   - Header with nav links (Link from `next/link`)
   - Footer
   - Metadata export for description, links

2. **`app/page.tsx`** — Home page (replaces `pages/index.js`)
   - Async server component
   - Fetch data directly (no getServerSideProps — use `fetch` with `cache: 'no-store'` for dynamic behavior)
   - Actually, looking at the original, it used `getServerSideProps` with `userAgent`. For the user-agent part, we need to use `headers()` from `next/headers` in a server component, or just skip it since the docs show we can access request headers in server components.
   - Wait, the original code used `userAgent` from `req.headers['user-agent']`. In App Router server components, we can use `headers()` from `next/headers`.
   - Use metadata export for head tags

3. **`app/blog/page.tsx`** — Blog listing (replaces `pages/blog/index.js`)
   - Async server component
   - fetch with `revalidate: 60` using `next: { revalidate: 60 }` fetch option
   - Metadata export
   - Use Link instead of `router.push` for navigation
   - Actually, the blog page used `useRouter` for programmatic navigation. In App Router, we can use `useRouter` from `next/navigation` in a client component. But since this is now a server component fetching data, we should use Link instead. Let me convert navigation to use Link or wrap the interactive parts in a client component.

4. **`app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`** — Blog post (replaces `pages/blog/[id].js`)
   - Async server component
   - `generateStaticParams` instead of `getStaticPaths`
   - `generateMetadata` for dynamic metadata
   - fetch with revalidation
   - `params` is a Promise in App Router
   - Use `notFound()` instead of `notFound: true` return

5. **`app/api/posts/route.ts`** — API route (replaces `pages/api/posts/index.js`)
6. **`app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`** — API route (replaces `pages/api/posts/[id].js`)
7. **`app/not-found.tsx`** — Not found page (replaces `_error.js` and `404.js` — not-found covers the 404 case)

8. **`app/error.tsx`** — Global error boundary (replaces `_error.js` for non-404 errors)
   - Must be a Client Component
   - Shows error info with reset capability

9. **Convert `components/AppProvider.js` to `components/AppProvider.tsx`** — Needs `'use client'` since it uses React context

Let me now think about how to handle the specific conversions:

### `pages/index.js` → `app/page.tsx`

In Pages Router with `getServerSideProps`, we get `req` to access `userAgent`. In App Router:
- The page is a Server Component by default
- Use `headers()` from `next/headers` to get user-agent
- Use `fetch` directly (it's an async component)
- For metadata, export a `metadata` object

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next'
import { headers } from 'next/headers'
import Link from 'next/link'

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Home - My Blog',
  description: 'Welcome to my blog homepage',
  openGraph: {
    title: 'Home - My Blog',
  },
}

export default async function HomePage() {
  const headersList = await headers()
  const userAgent = headersList.get('user-agent') || ''

  const posts = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?_limit=5')
    .then(res => res.json())

  const timestamp = new Date().toISOString()

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Welcome to My Blog</h1>
      <p>Server-side rendered at: {timestamp}</p>
      <p>Your user agent: {userAgent}</p>

      <h2>Recent Posts</h2>
      <ul>
        {posts.map(post => (
          <li key={post.id}>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <Link href="/blog">
        View All Posts
      </Link>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Wait — the original had `navigateToBlog` as a button with `router.push`. In App Router, we should use `<Link>` instead. The user wants proper modernization.

### `pages/blog/index.js` → `app/blog/page.tsx`

The original used `getStaticProps` with `revalidate: 60` (ISR). In App Router:
- Async server component fetches data directly
- Use `fetch` with `next: { revalidate: 60 }` for ISR
- For metadata, export `metadata` object
- Replace `router.push` with `Link`

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next'
import Link from 'next/link'

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'Blog - My Blog',
  description: 'All blog posts',
}

export default async function BlogIndex() {
  const posts = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts', {
    next: { revalidate: 60 },
  }).then(res => res.json())

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>All Blog Posts</h1>

      <div className="posts-grid">
        {posts.map(post => (
          <div key={post.id} className="post-card">
            <h2>
              <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
            </h2>
            <p>{post.body.substring(0, 100)}...</p>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>
              Read More
            </Link>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  )
}
```

### `pages/blog/[id].js` → `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`

In App Router:
- `params` is a `Promise<{ id: string }>`
- `generateStaticParams` instead of `getStaticPaths`
- `generateMetadata` for dynamic metadata
- `notFound()` from `next/navigation` instead of `notFound: true`
- Async component

Key differences:
- `fallback: 'blocking'` → In App Router, this is handled by `dynamicParams: true` (default) and having `generateStaticParams` return some paths
- Use `notFound()` when fetch fails

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next'
import { notFound } from 'next/navigation'
import Link from 'next/link'

interface Post {
  id: number
  title: string
  body: string
}

interface Comment {
  id: number
  name: string
  email: string
  body: string
}

interface Props {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>
}

export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const posts = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts')
    .then(res => res.json() as Promise<Post[]>)

  return posts.slice(0, 10).map(post => ({
    id: post.id.toString()
  }))
}

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params
  const post = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`)
    .then(res => res.json() as Promise<Post>)

  return {
    title: `${post.title} - My Blog`,
    description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    openGraph: {
      title: post.title,
      description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    },
  }
}

export default async function BlogPost({ params }: Props) {
  const { id } = await params

  try {
    const [post, comments] = await Promise.all([
      fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`, {
        next: { revalidate: 300 },
      }).then(res => res.json() as Promise<Post>),
      fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}/comments`, {
        next: { revalidate: 300 },
      }).then(res => res.json() as Promise<Comment[]>),
    ])

    return (
      <article>
        <Link href="/blog">← Back</Link>

        <h1>{post.title}</h1>
        <p>{post.body}</p>

        <h2>Comments ({comments.length})</h2>
        <div className="comments">
          {comments.map(comment => (
            <div key={comment.id} className="comment">
              <h3>{comment.name}</h3>
              <p>{comment.body}</p>
              <small>By: {comment.email}</small>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </article>
    )
  } catch {
    notFound()
  }
}
```

### `pages/api/posts/index.js` → `app/api/posts/route.ts`

In App Router, route handlers use named exports for HTTP methods and use web Request/Response APIs.

```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server'

interface Post {
  id: number
  title: string
  content: string
  createdAt?: string
}

const posts: Post[] = [
  { id: 1, title: 'First Post', content: 'This is the first post' },
  { id: 2, title: 'Second Post', content: 'This is the second post' }
]

export async function GET() {
  return NextResponse.json(posts)
}

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json()
  const { title, content } = body

  if (!title || !content) {
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: 'Title and content are required' },
      { status: 400 }
    )
  }

  const newPost: Post = {
    id: Date.now(),
    title,
    content,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString()
  }

  return NextResponse.json(newPost, { status: 201 })
}
```

Wait, the original doesn't use a persistent array, but I should keep the behavior the same. Actually, looking at the original, the posts array is local to the handler function, so each time it's called, it returns the same hardcoded array. Let me keep it that way for migration fidelity but note that's the original behavior.

Actually, looking more carefully, the original had:
```js
export default function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === 'GET') {
    const posts = [ ... ];
    res.status(200).json(posts);
  } else if (req.method === 'POST') {
    ...
  } else {
    res.setHeader('Allow', ['GET', 'POST']);
    res.status(405).end(`Method ${req.method} Not Allowed`);
  }
}
```

For the POST handler, `req.body` in Pages Router is parsed by Next.js. In App Router, we use `request.json()`.

### `pages/api/posts/[id].js` → `app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`

```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server'

interface Post {
  id: number
  title: string
  content: string
  createdAt?: string
  updatedAt?: string
}

export async function GET(
  _request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params
  const post: Post = {
    id: parseInt(id),
    title: `Post ${id}`,
    content: `This is the content for post ${id}`,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString()
  }
  return NextResponse.json(post)
}

export async function PUT(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params
  const body = await request.json()
  const { title, content } = body

  const updatedPost: Post = {
    id: parseInt(id),
    title: title || `Post ${id}`,
    content: content || `Updated content for post ${id}`,
    updatedAt: new Date().toISOString()
  }

  return NextResponse.json(updatedPost)
}

export async function DELETE(
  _request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params
  return NextResponse.json({ message: `Post ${id} deleted successfully` })
}
```

### `app/not-found.tsx` — replaces `404.js` and the 404 path in `_error.js`

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link'

export default function NotFound() {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>404 - Page Not Found</h1>
      <p>The page you&apos;re looking for doesn&apos;t exist.</p>
      <Link href="/">Go Back Home</Link>
    </div>
  )
}
```

### `app/error.tsx` — replaces `_error.js` for uncaught exceptions

```tsx
'use client'

export default function ErrorPage({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string }
  reset: () => void
}) {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>
        {error.message ? `A ${error.message} error occurred` : 'An error occurred'}
      </h1>
      <p>Sorry, something went wrong.</p>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try Again</button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Actually, the original `_error.js` was more nuanced — it showed different messages for 404 vs other errors and had `getInitialProps`. In App Router, 404s are handled by `not-found.tsx`, and other errors by `error.tsx`. So we split the logic.

### `app/layout.tsx` — Root layout

This is the most important file. It combines `_app.js` and `_document.js`.

```tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next'
import './globals.css'
import { AppProvider } from '@/components/AppProvider'

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  description: 'A complex blog application',
}

export default function RootLayout({
  children,
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode
}) {
  return (
    <html lang="en">
      <head>
        <link rel="icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
        <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
        <link 
          href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&display=swap" 
          rel="stylesheet" 
        />
      </head>
      <body>
        <AppProvider>
          <div className="app-container">
            <header>
              <h1>My Blog</h1>
              <nav>
                <a href="/">Home</a>
                <a href="/blog">Blog</a>
              </nav>
            </header>
            <main>
              {children}
            </main>
            <footer>
              <p>&copy; 2024 My Blog</p>
            </footer>
          </div>
        </AppProvider>
      </body>
    </html>
  )
}
